						href="https://reason.com/2020/10/05/the-post-pandemic-new-normal-looks-awfully-authoritarian/#comment-8501788">
						October.5.2020 at 1:25 pm					</a>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="comment-meta user-moderation-tools">
							</div>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content">
			<p>Even where it was the primary cause of death, it was often the primary cause of death of people who were dying and had months or even weeks left to live anyway. </p> <p>The contrast between that and H1N1 is striking. Virtually no one under the age of 18 has died from COVID in this country. Over 20,000 people under the age of 18 died in 2009 from H1N1</p> <p><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3128617/" rel="nofollow ugc">https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3128617/</a></p> <p>I think those 20,000 deaths are a much bigger tragedy in the scheme of things than even 200,000 deaths of people in their 70s and 80s who were close to death as it was. Every life matters but the death of a young person is a bigger tragedy by any objective measure.</p>		</div>

